Genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Peters, 1877" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1877" class="Reptilia" family="Pythonidae" genus="Aspidites" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidites" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aspidites Peters, 1877</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="37" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="37">Remarks:</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="37">
<bibRefCitation author="Henderson, RW" editor="Henderson, RW" journalOrPublisher="Eagle Mountain Publishing, Utah, USA" pageId="24" pageNumber="53" pagination="3 - 21" title="The biology of boas and pythons: a retrospective look to the future." volumeTitle="Biology of the Boas and Pythons." year="2007">Henderson and Powell (2007)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Swan M, (Ed)" journalOrPublisher="Mike Swan Herp Books, Lilydale, Victoria, Australia" pageId="25" pageNumber="54" title="Keeping and Breeding Australian Pythons." year="2007">Swan (2007)</bibRefCitation>
did not list subspecies within 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Pythonidae" genus="Aspidites" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidites" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aspidites</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Pythonidae" genus="Aspidites" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidites" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aspidites</taxonomicName>
was considered most primitive within the 
<taxonomicName family="Pythonidae" lsidName="" pageId="8" pageNumber="37" rank="family">Pythonidae</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Stimson, AF" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Zoological Nomenclature" pageId="25" pageNumber="54" pagination="330 - 334" title="Liasis Gray, 1842 (Reptilia, Serpentes): proposed designation of Liasis mackloti Dumeril and Bibron 1844 as type species Z. N. (S) 2439." volume="43" year="1986">Stimson and Underwood 1990</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kluge, AG" journalOrPublisher="Records of the Australian Museum Supplement" pageId="25" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 79" title="Aspidites and the phylogeny of pythonine snakes." volume="19" year="1993">Kluge 1993</bibRefCitation>
) due to a lack of thermoreceptive pits in the labial scales. However, current research (
<bibRefCitation pageId="8" pageNumber="37">Westhoff and Collin 2008</bibRefCitation>
) has revealed that 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Pythonidae" genus="Aspidites" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidites" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Aspidites</taxonomicName>
possesses a single thermoreceptive pit within the rostralia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
